[
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Presentation/Containers/Spectrum/Library/View/SpectrumRow/SpectrumRowInfoView.swift",
    "line": 39,
    "summary": "`if let cps { }` guard removed — CountRateLabelView(value: cps) now always rendered",
    "failure_scenario": "When a spectrum entry has no CPS data (cps == nil), the old code showed nothing. The new code unconditionally renders CountRateLabelView(value: nil), which produces '--cps' (or '--cpm') in the row. Every spectrum row without CPS data will show a spurious '--cps' label next to the duration."
  },
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Presentation/Containers/Radiationlevel/Charts/RadiationLevelView/ChartView/DGChartsHelpers/ChartAxisFormatter.swift",
    "line": 38,
    "summary": "PrecisionAxisValueFormatter countRate path scales tick values by ×60 for cpm mode but DGCharts data is always raw cps",
    "failure_scenario": "CountRateFormatted multiplies rawValue by 60 when unit == .cpm. DGCharts chart data is emitted and stored as raw cps floats (RadiationLevelViewModel stores count: $0.value unchanged). When the user switches to cpm, the Y-axis labels show cpm-scaled numbers while the plotted line heights correspond to cps values, making every tick label incorrect by a factor of 60."
  },
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Utils/Extensions/Double+Compare.swift",
    "line": 27,
    "summary": "isNearlyEqual uses absolute tolerance Float.ulpOfOne (~1.19e-7) which is effectively zero for real spectrum energy values",
    "failure_scenario": "In HardnessChartViewModel.findIsotope, the guard `!(currentValue ?? 0).isNearlyEqual(to: floatValue)` is intended to throttle isotope lookup when the cursor barely moves. Float.ulpOfOne is 1.19e-7; two adjacent Float representable values at ~662 keV differ by ~7.9e-5, which is ~650× larger than the tolerance. The guard almost never fires, so findIsotope and its O(n) isotope scan runs on every drag-frame update instead of being throttled."
  },
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Model/RadiationLabel/DoseFormatted.swift",
    "line": 51,
    "summary": "Nil rawValue branch hard-codes prefix = \"μ\" regardless of the unit type",
    "failure_scenario": "When rawValue is nil and unit == .rem, unitString becomes \"μrem\". This is arguably correct, but the value nil is reached before any scaling, so the nil-state unit string depends entirely on the hard-coded \"μ\" prefix rather than reflecting the actual display range. If the user's non-nil dose value would have shown \"mrem\" or \"rem\", the nil placeholder still reads \"--μrem\", which is inconsistent with the units shown once the device connects."
  },
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Presentation/Containers/Dose/DoseChartView/Model/DosePage.swift",
    "line": 24,
    "summary": "Float equality guard in recalculateDisplayedDose may cause spurious or missed @MainActor updates",
    "failure_scenario": "totalDisplayedDose changed from Decimal (exact) to Float. `guard newValue != totalDisplayedDose` now does a bitwise Float comparison on a value produced by reducing many Float bars. Floating-point addition is not associative; if bars are recalculated in different order on re-entry (after bar exclusion toggles), the sum may not be bitwise-identical even with equal logical totals, firing unnecessary Task { @MainActor in … } updates. Conversely, two 'different' doses that round to the same Float will be silently skipped."
  },
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Presentation/Containers/Dose/DoseChartView/Views/DoseChartYAxis.swift",
    "line": 39,
    "summary": "AxisMarks $0.as(Float.self) may yield no labels if Swift Charts infers a Double axis from the RuleMark's .value(_, Float)",
    "failure_scenario": "DoseChartYAxis contains only a RuleMark and an AxisMarks block — no BarMark/LineMark to drive axis-type inference. chartYScale(domain: 0 ... viewModel.maxY) where maxY is Float sets a ClosedRange<Float> domain. If Swift Charts normalises the inferred axis type to Double internally (as it historically has for non-BarMark charts), $0.as(Float.self) will always return nil and all Y-axis labels will be invisible. The previous code used Double.self and Double maxY, which worked reliably."
  },
  {
    "file": "RadiaCode/Presentation/Containers/ControlCenter/DeviceInfo/Views/AlarmLevels/AlarmLevelSetupViewModel.swift",
    "line": 62,
    "summary": "makeValues step-boundary logic subtracts nextStep (finer) instead of currentStep at power-of-10 boundaries, producing a doubled value near transitions",
    "failure_scenario": "At a step-size transition (e.g. value = 20 for doseRate, where step switches from 0.1 to 0.01): currentStep = 0.1, next = 19.9, nextStep = 0.01. Since nextStep < currentStep, the new code sets value = 20 − 0.01 = 19.99. The sequence becomes …20.0, 19.99, 19.98… instead of …20.0, 19.9, 19.8…. This inserts a spurious 19.99 entry in the wheel immediately below the 20.0 boundary entry, rather than the expected 19.9, causing the first step after the boundary to look like a near-duplicate to the user."
  },
